{"cues": [{"duration": 1.967, "start": 0.0, "text": "In the last chapter, you and I started to step"}, {"duration": 2.053, "start": 1.967, "text": "through the internal workings of a transformer."}, {"duration": 3.32, "start": 4.56, "text": "This is one of the key pieces of technology inside large language models,"}, {"duration": 2.32, "start": 7.88, "text": "and a lot of other tools in the modern wave of AI."}, {"duration": 4.54, "start": 10.98, "text": "It first hit the scene in a now-famous 2017 paper called Attention is All You Need,"}, {"duration": 4.266, "start": 15.52, "text": "and in this chapter you and I will dig into what this attention mechanism is,"}, {"duration": 1.914, "start": 19.786, "text": "visualizing how it processes data."}, {"duration": 3.4, "start": 26.14, "text": "As a quick recap, here's the important context I want you to have in mind."}, {"duration": 2.95, "start": 30.0, "text": "The goal of the model that you and I are studying is to"}, {"duration": 3.11, "start": 32.95, "text": "take in a piece of text and predict what word comes next."}, {"duration": 3.477, "start": 36.86, "text": "The input text is broken up into little pieces that we call tokens,"}, {"duration": 2.646, "start": 40.337, "text": "and these are very often words or pieces of words,"}, {"duration": 4.256, "start": 42.983, "text": "but just to make the examples in this video easier for you and me to think about,"}, {"duration": 3.321, "start": 47.239, "text": "let's simplify by pretending that tokens are always just words."}, {"duration": 3.057, "start": 51.48, "text": "The first step in a transformer is to associate each token"}, {"duration": 3.163, "start": 54.537, "text": "with a high-dimensional vector, what we call its embedding."}, {"duration": 4.31, "start": 57.7, "text": "The most important idea I want you to have in mind is how directions in this"}, {"duration": 4.99, "start": 62.01, "text": "high-dimensional space of all possible embeddings can correspond with semantic meaning."}, {"duration": 4.036, "start": 67.68, "text": "In the last chapter we saw an example for how direction can correspond to gender,"}, {"duration": 3.788, "start": 71.716, "text": "in the sense that adding a certain step in this space can take you from the"}, {"duration": 4.136, "start": 75.504, "text": "embedding of a masculine noun to the embedding of the corresponding feminine noun."}, {"duration": 3.435, "start": 80.16, "text": "That's just one example you could imagine how many other directions in this"}, {"duration": 3.985, "start": 83.595, "text": "high-dimensional space could correspond to numerous other aspects of a word's meaning."}, {"duration": 3.735, "start": 88.8, "text": "The aim of a transformer is to progressively adjust these embeddings"}, {"duration": 2.91, "start": 92.535, "text": "so that they don't merely encode an individual word,"}, {"duration": 3.735, "start": 95.445, "text": "but instead they bake in some much, much richer contextual meaning."}, {"duration": 3.516, "start": 100.14, "text": "I should say up front that a lot of people find the attention mechanism,"}, {"duration": 2.394, "start": 103.656, "text": "this key piece in a transformer, very confusing,"}, {"duration": 2.93, "start": 106.05, "text": "so don't worry if it takes some time for things to sink in."}, {"duration": 3.256, "start": 109.44, "text": "I think that before we dive into the computational details and all"}, {"duration": 3.109, "start": 112.696, "text": "the matrix multiplications, it's worth thinking about a couple"}, {"duration": 3.355, "start": 115.805, "text": "examples for the kind of behavior that we want attention to enable."}, {"duration": 4.195, "start": 120.14, "text": "Consider the phrases American shrew mole, one mole of carbon dioxide,"}, {"duration": 1.885, "start": 124.335, "text": "and take a biopsy of the mole."}, {"duration": 3.276, "start": 126.7, "text": "You and I know that the word mole has different meanings in each one of these,"}, {"duration": 0.924, "start": 129.976, "text": "based on the context."}, {"duration": 3.715, "start": 131.36, "text": "But after the first step of a transformer, the one that breaks up the text"}, {"duration": 3.765, "start": 135.075, "text": "and associates each token with a vector, the vector that's associated with"}, {"duration": 2.31, "start": 138.84, "text": "mole would be the same in all of these cases,"}, {"duration": 3.765, "start": 141.15, "text": "because this initial token embedding is effectively a lookup table with no"}, {"duration": 1.305, "start": 144.915, "text": "reference to the context."}, {"duration": 3.341, "start": 146.62, "text": "It's only in the next step of the transformer that the surrounding"}, {"duration": 3.139, "start": 149.961, "text": "embeddings have the chance to pass information into this one."}, {"duration": 4.468, "start": 153.82, "text": "The picture you might have in mind is that there are multiple distinct directions in"}, {"duration": 4.203, "start": 158.288, "text": "this embedding space encoding the multiple distinct meanings of the word mole,"}, {"duration": 4.628, "start": 162.491, "text": "and that a well-trained attention block calculates what you need to add to the generic"}, {"duration": 4.681, "start": 167.119, "text": "embedding to move it to one of these specific directions, as a function of the context."}, {"duration": 2.88, "start": 173.3, "text": "To take another example, consider the embedding of the word tower."}, {"duration": 4.007, "start": 177.06, "text": "This is presumably some very generic, non-specific direction in the space,"}, {"duration": 2.653, "start": 181.067, "text": "associated with lots of other large, tall nouns."}, {"duration": 2.569, "start": 184.02, "text": "If this word was immediately preceded by Eiffel,"}, {"duration": 3.747, "start": 186.589, "text": "you could imagine wanting the mechanism to update this vector so that"}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 190.336, "text": "it points in a direction that more specifically encodes the Eiffel tower,"}, {"duration": 4.764, "start": 194.296, "text": "maybe correlated with vectors associated with Paris and France and things made of steel."}, {"duration": 2.309, "start": 199.92, "text": "If it was also preceded by the word miniature,"}, {"duration": 2.41, "start": 202.229, "text": "then the vector should be updated even further,"}, {"duration": 2.861, "start": 204.639, "text": "so that it no longer correlates with large, tall things."}, {"duration": 2.794, "start": 209.48, "text": "More generally than just refining the meaning of a word,"}, {"duration": 3.393, "start": 212.274, "text": "the attention block allows the model to move information encoded in"}, {"duration": 3.791, "start": 215.667, "text": "one embedding to that of another, potentially ones that are quite far away,"}, {"duration": 3.842, "start": 219.458, "text": "and potentially with information that's much richer than just a single word."}, {"duration": 4.631, "start": 223.3, "text": "What we saw in the last chapter was how after all of the vectors flow through the"}, {"duration": 2.973, "start": 227.931, "text": "network, including many different attention blocks,"}, {"duration": 4.803, "start": 230.904, "text": "the computation you perform to produce a prediction of the next token is entirely a"}, {"duration": 2.573, "start": 235.707, "text": "function of the last vector in the sequence."}, {"duration": 4.35, "start": 239.1, "text": "Imagine, for example, that the text you input is most of an entire mystery novel,"}, {"duration": 4.35, "start": 243.45, "text": "all the way up to a point near the end, which reads, therefore the murderer was."}, {"duration": 3.057, "start": 248.4, "text": "If the model is going to accurately predict the next word,"}, {"duration": 4.586, "start": 251.457, "text": "that final vector in the sequence, which began its life simply embedding the word was,"}, {"duration": 4.27, "start": 256.043, "text": "will have to have been updated by all of the attention blocks to represent much,"}, {"duration": 4.006, "start": 260.313, "text": "much more than any individual word, somehow encoding all of the information"}, {"duration": 3.901, "start": 264.319, "text": "from the full context window that's relevant to predicting the next word."}, {"duration": 3.08, "start": 269.5, "text": "To step through the computations, though, let's take a much simpler example."}, {"duration": 2.41, "start": 272.98, "text": "Imagine that the input includes the phrase, a"}, {"duration": 2.57, "start": 275.39, "text": "fluffy blue creature roamed the verdant forest."}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 278.46, "text": "And for the moment, suppose that the only type of update that we care about"}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 282.62, "text": "is having the adjectives adjust the meanings of their corresponding nouns."}, {"duration": 3.72, "start": 287.0, "text": "What I'm about to describe is what we would call a single head of attention,"}, {"duration": 4.21, "start": 290.72, "text": "and later we will see how the attention block consists of many different heads run in"}, {"duration": 0.49, "start": 294.93, "text": "parallel."}, {"duration": 3.695, "start": 296.14, "text": "Again, the initial embedding for each word is some high dimensional vector"}, {"duration": 3.545, "start": 299.835, "text": "that only encodes the meaning of that particular word with no context."}, {"duration": 1.22, "start": 304.0, "text": "Actually, that's not quite true."}, {"duration": 2.26, "start": 305.38, "text": "They also encode the position of the word."}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 307.98, "text": "There's a lot more to say about the specific way that positions are encoded,"}, {"duration": 3.592, "start": 311.62, "text": "but right now, all you need to know is that the entries of this vector are"}, {"duration": 3.688, "start": 315.212, "text": "enough to tell you both what the word is and where it exists in the context."}, {"duration": 2.16, "start": 319.5, "text": "Let's go ahead and denote these embeddings with the letter e."}, {"duration": 3.63, "start": 322.42, "text": "The goal is to have a series of computations produce a new refined"}, {"duration": 3.575, "start": 326.05, "text": "set of embeddings where, for example, those corresponding to the"}, {"duration": 3.795, "start": 329.625, "text": "nouns have ingested the meaning from their corresponding adjectives."}, {"duration": 3.249, "start": 333.9, "text": "And playing the deep learning game, we want most of the computations"}, {"duration": 2.197, "start": 337.149, "text": "involved to look like matrix-vector products,"}, {"duration": 2.341, "start": 339.346, "text": "where the matrices are full of tuneable weights,"}, {"duration": 2.293, "start": 341.687, "text": "things that the model will learn based on data."}, {"duration": 3.703, "start": 344.66, "text": "To be clear, I'm making up this example of adjectives updating nouns just to"}, {"duration": 3.897, "start": 348.363, "text": "illustrate the type of behavior that you could imagine an attention head doing."}, {"duration": 4.143, "start": 352.86, "text": "As with so much deep learning, the true behavior is much harder to parse because it's"}, {"duration": 4.337, "start": 357.003, "text": "based on tweaking and tuning a huge number of parameters to minimize some cost function."}, {"duration": 3.878, "start": 361.68, "text": "It's just that as we step through all of different matrices filled with parameters"}, {"duration": 3.926, "start": 365.558, "text": "that are involved in this process, I think it's really helpful to have an imagined"}, {"duration": 3.736, "start": 369.484, "text": "example of something that it could be doing to help keep it all more concrete."}, {"duration": 4.012, "start": 374.14, "text": "For the first step of this process, you might imagine each noun, like creature,"}, {"duration": 3.808, "start": 378.152, "text": "asking the question, hey, are there any adjectives sitting in front of me?"}, {"duration": 3.216, "start": 382.16, "text": "And for the words fluffy and blue, to each be able to answer,"}, {"duration": 2.584, "start": 385.376, "text": "yeah, I'm an adjective and I'm in that position."}, {"duration": 3.3, "start": 388.96, "text": "That question is somehow encoded as yet another vector,"}, {"duration": 3.84, "start": 392.26, "text": "another list of numbers, which we call the query for this word."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 396.98, "text": "This query vector though has a much smaller dimension than the embedding vector, say 128."}, {"duration": 3.36, "start": 402.94, "text": "Computing this query looks like taking a certain matrix,"}, {"duration": 3.48, "start": 406.3, "text": "which I'll label wq, and multiplying it by the embedding."}, {"duration": 3.21, "start": 410.96, "text": "Compressing things a bit, let's write that query vector as q,"}, {"duration": 3.842, "start": 414.17, "text": "and then anytime you see me put a matrix next to an arrow like this one,"}, {"duration": 4.63, "start": 418.012, "text": "it's meant to represent that multiplying this matrix by the vector at the arrow's start"}, {"duration": 2.158, "start": 422.642, "text": "gives you the vector at the arrow's end."}, {"duration": 4.351, "start": 425.86, "text": "In this case, you multiply this matrix by all of the embeddings in the context,"}, {"duration": 2.369, "start": 430.211, "text": "producing one query vector for each token."}, {"duration": 2.641, "start": 433.74, "text": "The entries of this matrix are parameters of the model,"}, {"duration": 3.313, "start": 436.381, "text": "which means the true behavior is learned from data, and in practice,"}, {"duration": 3.746, "start": 439.694, "text": "what this matrix does in a particular attention head is challenging to parse."}, {"duration": 3.996, "start": 443.9, "text": "But for our sake, imagining an example that we might hope that it would learn,"}, {"duration": 3.535, "start": 447.896, "text": "we'll suppose that this query matrix maps the embeddings of nouns to"}, {"duration": 3.484, "start": 451.431, "text": "certain directions in this smaller query space that somehow encodes"}, {"duration": 3.125, "start": 454.915, "text": "the notion of looking for adjectives in preceding positions."}, {"duration": 2.66, "start": 458.78, "text": "As to what it does to other embeddings, who knows?"}, {"duration": 2.62, "start": 461.72, "text": "Maybe it simultaneously tries to accomplish some other goal with those."}, {"duration": 2.62, "start": 464.54, "text": "Right now, we're laser focused on the nouns."}, {"duration": 4.318, "start": 467.28, "text": "At the same time, associated with this is a second matrix called the key matrix,"}, {"duration": 3.022, "start": 471.598, "text": "which you also multiply by every one of the embeddings."}, {"duration": 3.22, "start": 475.28, "text": "This produces a second sequence of vectors that we call the keys."}, {"duration": 3.72, "start": 479.42, "text": "Conceptually, you want to think of the keys as potentially answering the queries."}, {"duration": 4.124, "start": 483.84, "text": "This key matrix is also full of tuneable parameters, and just like the query matrix,"}, {"duration": 3.436, "start": 487.964, "text": "it maps the embedding vectors to that same smaller dimensional space."}, {"duration": 4.82, "start": 492.2, "text": "You think of the keys as matching the queries whenever they closely align with each other."}, {"duration": 4.693, "start": 497.46, "text": "In our example, you would imagine that the key matrix maps the adjectives like fluffy and"}, {"duration": 4.587, "start": 502.153, "text": "blue to vectors that are closely aligned with the query produced by the word creature."}, {"duration": 2.914, "start": 507.2, "text": "To measure how well each key matches each query,"}, {"duration": 3.886, "start": 510.114, "text": "you compute a dot product between each possible key-query pair."}, {"duration": 2.625, "start": 514.48, "text": "I like to visualize a grid full of a bunch of dots,"}, {"duration": 3.139, "start": 517.105, "text": "where the bigger dots correspond to the larger dot products,"}, {"duration": 2.316, "start": 520.244, "text": "the places where the keys and queries align."}, {"duration": 4.197, "start": 523.28, "text": "For our adjective noun example, that would look a little more like this,"}, {"duration": 4.955, "start": 527.477, "text": "where if the keys produced by fluffy and blue really do align closely with the query"}, {"duration": 4.839, "start": 532.432, "text": "produced by creature, then the dot products in these two spots would be some large"}, {"duration": 1.049, "start": 537.271, "text": "positive numbers."}, {"duration": 3.16, "start": 539.1, "text": "In the lingo, machine learning people would say that this means the"}, {"duration": 3.16, "start": 542.26, "text": "embeddings of fluffy and blue attend to the embedding of creature."}, {"duration": 3.426, "start": 546.04, "text": "By contrast to the dot product between the key for some other"}, {"duration": 3.427, "start": 549.466, "text": "word like the and the query for creature would be some small"}, {"duration": 3.707, "start": 552.893, "text": "or negative value that reflects that are unrelated to each other."}, {"duration": 3.632, "start": 557.7, "text": "So we have this grid of values that can be any real number from"}, {"duration": 3.804, "start": 561.332, "text": "negative infinity to infinity, giving us a score for how relevant"}, {"duration": 3.344, "start": 565.136, "text": "each word is to updating the meaning of every other word."}, {"duration": 3.318, "start": 569.2, "text": "The way we're about to use these scores is to take a certain"}, {"duration": 3.262, "start": 572.518, "text": "weighted sum along each column, weighted by the relevance."}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 576.52, "text": "So instead of having values range from negative infinity to infinity,"}, {"duration": 3.799, "start": 580.16, "text": "what we want is for the numbers in these columns to be between 0 and 1,"}, {"duration": 4.221, "start": 583.959, "text": "and for each column to add up to 1, as if they were a probability distribution."}, {"duration": 2.94, "start": 589.28, "text": "If you're coming in from the last chapter, you know what we need to do then."}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 592.62, "text": "We compute a softmax along each one of these columns to normalize the values."}, {"duration": 3.127, "start": 600.06, "text": "In our picture, after you apply softmax to all of the columns,"}, {"duration": 2.673, "start": 603.187, "text": "we'll fill in the grid with these normalized values."}, {"duration": 3.925, "start": 606.78, "text": "At this point you're safe to think about each column as giving weights according"}, {"duration": 3.875, "start": 610.705, "text": "to how relevant the word on the left is to the corresponding value at the top."}, {"duration": 1.76, "start": 615.08, "text": "We call this grid an attention pattern."}, {"duration": 2.155, "start": 618.08, "text": "Now if you look at the original transformer paper,"}, {"duration": 2.585, "start": 620.235, "text": "there's a really compact way that they write this all down."}, {"duration": 3.548, "start": 623.88, "text": "Here the variables q and k represent the full arrays of query"}, {"duration": 3.606, "start": 627.428, "text": "and key vectors respectively, those little vectors you get by"}, {"duration": 3.606, "start": 631.034, "text": "multiplying the embeddings by the query and the key matrices."}, {"duration": 3.903, "start": 635.16, "text": "This expression up in the numerator is a really compact way to represent"}, {"duration": 3.957, "start": 639.063, "text": "the grid of all possible dot products between pairs of keys and queries."}, {"duration": 4.035, "start": 644.0, "text": "A small technical detail that I didn't mention is that for numerical stability,"}, {"duration": 3.167, "start": 648.035, "text": "it happens to be helpful to divide all of these values by the"}, {"duration": 2.758, "start": 651.202, "text": "square root of the dimension in that key query space."}, {"duration": 3.329, "start": 654.48, "text": "Then this softmax that's wrapped around the full expression"}, {"duration": 2.991, "start": 657.809, "text": "is meant to be understood to apply column by column."}, {"duration": 3.06, "start": 661.64, "text": "As to that v term, we'll talk about it in just a second."}, {"duration": 3.44, "start": 665.02, "text": "Before that, there's one other technical detail that so far I've skipped."}, {"duration": 3.959, "start": 669.04, "text": "During the training process, when you run this model on a given text example,"}, {"duration": 4.37, "start": 672.999, "text": "and all of the weights are slightly adjusted and tuned to either reward or punish it"}, {"duration": 4.165, "start": 677.369, "text": "based on how high a probability it assigns to the true next word in the passage,"}, {"duration": 3.908, "start": 681.534, "text": "it turns out to make the whole training process a lot more efficient if you"}, {"duration": 4.113, "start": 685.442, "text": "simultaneously have it predict every possible next token following each initial"}, {"duration": 2.005, "start": 689.555, "text": "subsequence of tokens in this passage."}, {"duration": 2.936, "start": 691.94, "text": "For example, with the phrase that we've been focusing on,"}, {"duration": 4.224, "start": 694.876, "text": "it might also be predicting what words follow creature and what words follow the."}, {"duration": 2.885, "start": 699.94, "text": "This is really nice, because it means what would otherwise"}, {"duration": 2.735, "start": 702.825, "text": "be a single training example effectively acts as many."}, {"duration": 3.33, "start": 706.1, "text": "For the purposes of our attention pattern, it means that you never"}, {"duration": 2.725, "start": 709.43, "text": "want to allow later words to influence earlier words,"}, {"duration": 3.885, "start": 712.155, "text": "since otherwise they could kind of give away the answer for what comes next."}, {"duration": 3.002, "start": 716.56, "text": "What this means is that we want all of these spots here,"}, {"duration": 3.269, "start": 719.562, "text": "the ones representing later tokens influencing earlier ones,"}, {"duration": 1.769, "start": 722.831, "text": "to somehow be forced to be zero."}, {"duration": 2.791, "start": 725.92, "text": "The simplest thing you might think to do is to set them equal to zero,"}, {"duration": 2.553, "start": 728.711, "text": "but if you did that the columns wouldn't add up to one anymore,"}, {"duration": 1.156, "start": 731.264, "text": "they wouldn't be normalized."}, {"duration": 3.289, "start": 733.12, "text": "So instead, a common way to do this is that before applying softmax,"}, {"duration": 2.611, "start": 736.409, "text": "you set all of those entries to be negative infinity."}, {"duration": 3.879, "start": 739.68, "text": "If you do that, then after applying softmax, all of those get turned into zero,"}, {"duration": 1.621, "start": 743.559, "text": "but the columns stay normalized."}, {"duration": 1.54, "start": 746.0, "text": "This process is called masking."}, {"duration": 3.758, "start": 747.54, "text": "There are versions of attention where you don't apply it, but in our GPT example,"}, {"duration": 3.62, "start": 751.298, "text": "even though this is more relevant during the training phase than it would be,"}, {"duration": 2.459, "start": 754.918, "text": "say, running it as a chatbot or something like that,"}, {"duration": 4.083, "start": 757.377, "text": "you do always apply this masking to prevent later tokens from influencing earlier ones."}, {"duration": 3.291, "start": 762.48, "text": "Another fact that's worth reflecting on about this attention"}, {"duration": 3.729, "start": 765.771, "text": "pattern is how its size is equal to the square of the context size."}, {"duration": 4.099, "start": 769.9, "text": "So this is why context size can be a really huge bottleneck for large language models,"}, {"duration": 1.621, "start": 773.999, "text": "and scaling it up is non-trivial."}, {"duration": 3.775, "start": 776.3, "text": "As you imagine, motivated by a desire for bigger and bigger context windows,"}, {"duration": 4.073, "start": 780.075, "text": "recent years have seen some variations to the attention mechanism aimed at making"}, {"duration": 4.172, "start": 784.148, "text": "context more scalable, but right here, you and I are staying focused on the basics."}, {"duration": 2.365, "start": 790.56, "text": "Okay, great, computing this pattern lets the model"}, {"duration": 2.555, "start": 792.925, "text": "deduce which words are relevant to which other words."}, {"duration": 2.49, "start": 796.02, "text": "Now you need to actually update the embeddings,"}, {"duration": 4.29, "start": 798.51, "text": "allowing words to pass information to whichever other words they're relevant to."}, {"duration": 3.962, "start": 802.8, "text": "For example, you want the embedding of Fluffy to somehow cause a change"}, {"duration": 4.075, "start": 806.762, "text": "to Creature that moves it to a different part of this 12,000-dimensional"}, {"duration": 3.683, "start": 810.837, "text": "embedding space that more specifically encodes a Fluffy creature."}, {"duration": 2.863, "start": 815.46, "text": "What I'm going to do here is first show you the most straightforward"}, {"duration": 2.569, "start": 818.323, "text": "way that you could do this, though there's a slight way that"}, {"duration": 2.568, "start": 820.892, "text": "this gets modified in the context of multi-headed attention."}, {"duration": 3.035, "start": 824.08, "text": "This most straightforward way would be to use a third matrix,"}, {"duration": 4.33, "start": 827.115, "text": "what we call the value matrix, which you multiply by the embedding of that first word,"}, {"duration": 0.995, "start": 831.445, "text": "for example Fluffy."}, {"duration": 2.586, "start": 833.3, "text": "The result of this is what you would call a value vector,"}, {"duration": 3.267, "start": 835.886, "text": "and this is something that you add to the embedding of the second word,"}, {"duration": 2.767, "start": 839.153, "text": "in this case something you add to the embedding of Creature."}, {"duration": 4.4, "start": 842.6, "text": "So this value vector lives in the same very high-dimensional space as the embeddings."}, {"duration": 3.32, "start": 847.46, "text": "When you multiply this value matrix by the embedding of a word,"}, {"duration": 4.531, "start": 850.78, "text": "you might think of it as saying, if this word is relevant to adjusting the meaning of"}, {"duration": 4.479, "start": 855.311, "text": "something else, what exactly should be added to the embedding of that something else"}, {"duration": 1.37, "start": 859.79, "text": "in order to reflect this?"}, {"duration": 3.828, "start": 862.14, "text": "Looking back in our diagram, let's set aside all of the keys and the queries,"}, {"duration": 3.48, "start": 865.968, "text": "since after you compute the attention pattern you're done with those,"}, {"duration": 3.43, "start": 869.448, "text": "then you're going to take this value matrix and multiply it by every"}, {"duration": 3.182, "start": 872.878, "text": "one of those embeddings to produce a sequence of value vectors."}, {"duration": 1.979, "start": 877.12, "text": "You might think of these value vectors as being"}, {"duration": 2.021, "start": 879.099, "text": "kind of associated with the corresponding keys."}, {"duration": 3.43, "start": 882.32, "text": "For each column in this diagram, you multiply each of the"}, {"duration": 3.49, "start": 885.75, "text": "value vectors by the corresponding weight in that column."}, {"duration": 2.682, "start": 890.08, "text": "For example here, under the embedding of Creature,"}, {"duration": 4.292, "start": 892.762, "text": "you would be adding large proportions of the value vectors for Fluffy and Blue,"}, {"duration": 4.506, "start": 897.054, "text": "while all of the other value vectors get zeroed out, or at least nearly zeroed out."}, {"duration": 4.631, "start": 902.12, "text": "And then finally, the way to actually update the embedding associated with this column,"}, {"duration": 3.141, "start": 906.751, "text": "previously encoding some context-free meaning of Creature,"}, {"duration": 3.247, "start": 909.892, "text": "you add together all of these rescaled values in the column,"}, {"duration": 3.513, "start": 913.139, "text": "producing a change that you want to add, that I'll label delta-e,"}, {"duration": 2.608, "start": 916.652, "text": "and then you add that to the original embedding."}, {"duration": 3.436, "start": 919.68, "text": "Hopefully what results is a more refined vector encoding the more"}, {"duration": 3.384, "start": 923.116, "text": "contextually rich meaning, like that of a fluffy blue creature."}, {"duration": 2.792, "start": 927.38, "text": "And of course you don't just do this to one embedding,"}, {"duration": 3.878, "start": 930.172, "text": "you apply the same weighted sum across all of the columns in this picture,"}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 934.05, "text": "producing a sequence of changes, adding all of those changes to the corresponding"}, {"duration": 3.929, "start": 938.29, "text": "embeddings, produces a full sequence of more refined embeddings popping out"}, {"duration": 1.241, "start": 942.219, "text": "of the attention block."}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 944.86, "text": "Zooming out, this whole process is what you would describe as a single head of attention."}, {"duration": 4.641, "start": 949.6, "text": "As I've described things so far, this process is parameterized by three distinct"}, {"duration": 4.699, "start": 954.241, "text": "matrices, all filled with tunable parameters, the key, the query, and the value."}, {"duration": 3.435, "start": 959.5, "text": "I want to take a moment to continue what we started in the last chapter,"}, {"duration": 4.151, "start": 962.935, "text": "with the scorekeeping where we count up the total number of model parameters using the"}, {"duration": 0.954, "start": 967.086, "text": "numbers from GPT-3."}, {"duration": 5.737, "start": 969.3, "text": "These key and query matrices each have 12,288 columns, matching the embedding dimension,"}, {"duration": 4.563, "start": 975.037, "text": "and 128 rows, matching the dimension of that smaller key query space."}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 980.26, "text": "This gives us an additional 1.5 million or so parameters for each one."}, {"duration": 5.263, "start": 984.86, "text": "If you look at that value matrix by contrast, the way I've described things so"}, {"duration": 5.736, "start": 990.123, "text": "far would suggest that it's a square matrix that has 12,288 columns and 12,288 rows,"}, {"duration": 5.061, "start": 995.859, "text": "since both its inputs and outputs live in this very large embedding space."}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 1001.5, "text": "If true, that would mean about 150 million added parameters."}, {"duration": 1.64, "start": 1005.66, "text": "And to be clear, you could do that."}, {"duration": 2.34, "start": 1007.42, "text": "You could devote orders of magnitude more parameters"}, {"duration": 1.98, "start": 1009.76, "text": "to the value map than to the key and query."}, {"duration": 2.932, "start": 1012.06, "text": "But in practice, it is much more efficient if instead you make"}, {"duration": 2.931, "start": 1014.992, "text": "it so that the number of parameters devoted to this value map"}, {"duration": 2.837, "start": 1017.923, "text": "is the same as the number devoted to the key and the query."}, {"duration": 1.83, "start": 1021.46, "text": "This is especially relevant in the setting of"}, {"duration": 1.87, "start": 1023.29, "text": "running multiple attention heads in parallel."}, {"duration": 3.86, "start": 1026.24, "text": "The way this looks is that the value map is factored as a product of two smaller matrices."}, {"duration": 4.155, "start": 1031.18, "text": "Conceptually, I would still encourage you to think about the overall linear map,"}, {"duration": 3.427, "start": 1035.335, "text": "one with inputs and outputs, both in this larger embedding space,"}, {"duration": 4.311, "start": 1038.762, "text": "for example taking the embedding of blue to this blueness direction that you would"}, {"duration": 0.727, "start": 1043.073, "text": "add to nouns."}, {"duration": 3.298, "start": 1047.04, "text": "The first matrix on the right here has a smaller number of rows,"}, {"duration": 2.422, "start": 1050.338, "text": "typically the same size as the key-query space"}, {"duration": 2.645, "start": 1053.1, "text": "What this means is you can think of it as mapping the"}, {"duration": 2.695, "start": 1055.745, "text": "large embedding vectors down to a much smaller space."}, {"duration": 3.66, "start": 1059.04, "text": "This is not the conventional naming, but I'm going to call this the value down matrix."}, {"duration": 3.972, "start": 1063.4, "text": "The second matrix maps from this smaller space back up to the embedding space,"}, {"duration": 3.208, "start": 1067.372, "text": "producing the vectors that you use to make the actual updates."}, {"duration": 3.74, "start": 1071.0, "text": "I'm going to call this one the value up matrix, which again is not conventional."}, {"duration": 2.92, "start": 1075.16, "text": "The way that you would see this written in most papers looks a little different."}, {"duration": 1.14, "start": 1078.38, "text": "I'll talk about it in a minute."}, {"duration": 2.84, "start": 1079.7, "text": "In my opinion, it tends to make things a little more conceptually confusing."}, {"duration": 3.566, "start": 1083.26, "text": "To throw in linear algebra jargon here, what we're basically doing is"}, {"duration": 3.514, "start": 1086.826, "text": "constraining the overall value map to be a low rank transformation."}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 1091.42, "text": "Turning back to the parameter count, all four of these matrices have the same size,"}, {"duration": 4.68, "start": 1096.1, "text": "and adding them all up we get about 6.3 million parameters for one attention head."}, {"duration": 2.154, "start": 1102.04, "text": "As a quick side note, to be a little more accurate,"}, {"duration": 3.252, "start": 1104.194, "text": "everything described so far is what people would call a self-attention head,"}, {"duration": 3.04, "start": 1107.446, "text": "to distinguish it from a variation that comes up in other models that's"}, {"duration": 1.014, "start": 1110.486, "text": "called cross-attention."}, {"duration": 3.432, "start": 1112.3, "text": "This isn't relevant to our GPT example, but if you're curious,"}, {"duration": 4.042, "start": 1115.732, "text": "cross-attention involves models that process two distinct types of data,"}, {"duration": 4.041, "start": 1119.774, "text": "like text in one language and text in another language that's part of an"}, {"duration": 4.152, "start": 1123.815, "text": "ongoing generation of a translation, or maybe audio input of speech and an"}, {"duration": 1.273, "start": 1127.967, "text": "ongoing transcription."}, {"duration": 2.3, "start": 1130.4, "text": "A cross-attention head looks almost identical."}, {"duration": 4.42, "start": 1132.98, "text": "The only difference is that the key and query maps act on different data sets."}, {"duration": 4.218, "start": 1137.84, "text": "In a model doing translation, for example, the keys might come from one language,"}, {"duration": 4.061, "start": 1142.058, "text": "while the queries come from another, and the attention pattern could describe"}, {"duration": 3.541, "start": 1146.119, "text": "which words from one language correspond to which words in another."}, {"duration": 2.545, "start": 1150.34, "text": "And in this setting there would typically be no masking,"}, {"duration": 3.455, "start": 1152.885, "text": "since there's not really any notion of later tokens affecting earlier ones."}, {"duration": 3.586, "start": 1157.18, "text": "Staying focused on self-attention though, if you understood everything so far,"}, {"duration": 3.908, "start": 1160.766, "text": "and if you were to stop here, you would come away with the essence of what attention"}, {"duration": 0.506, "start": 1164.674, "text": "really is."}, {"duration": 2.954, "start": 1165.76, "text": "All that's really left to us is to lay out the sense"}, {"duration": 2.726, "start": 1168.714, "text": "in which you do this many many different times."}, {"duration": 3.032, "start": 1172.1, "text": "In our central example we focused on adjectives updating nouns,"}, {"duration": 3.754, "start": 1175.132, "text": "but of course there are lots of different ways that context can influence the"}, {"duration": 0.914, "start": 1178.886, "text": "meaning of a word."}, {"duration": 2.835, "start": 1180.36, "text": "If the words they crashed the preceded the word car,"}, {"duration": 3.325, "start": 1183.195, "text": "it has implications for the shape and structure of that car."}, {"duration": 2.08, "start": 1187.2, "text": "And a lot of associations might be less grammatical."}, {"duration": 3.123, "start": 1189.76, "text": "If the word wizard is anywhere in the same passage as Harry,"}, {"duration": 3.02, "start": 1192.883, "text": "it suggests that this might be referring to Harry Potter,"}, {"duration": 4.06, "start": 1195.903, "text": "whereas if instead the words Queen, Sussex, and William were in that passage,"}, {"duration": 4.477, "start": 1199.963, "text": "then perhaps the embedding of Harry should instead be updated to refer to the prince."}, {"duration": 3.5, "start": 1205.04, "text": "For every different type of contextual updating that you might imagine,"}, {"duration": 3.402, "start": 1208.54, "text": "the parameters of these key and query matrices would be different to"}, {"duration": 3.353, "start": 1211.942, "text": "capture the different attention patterns, and the parameters of our"}, {"duration": 3.845, "start": 1215.295, "text": "value map would be different based on what should be added to the embeddings."}, {"duration": 3.137, "start": 1219.98, "text": "And again, in practice the true behavior of these maps is much more"}, {"duration": 3.231, "start": 1223.117, "text": "difficult to interpret, where the weights are set to do whatever the"}, {"duration": 3.792, "start": 1226.348, "text": "model needs them to do to best accomplish its goal of predicting the next token."}, {"duration": 3.788, "start": 1231.4, "text": "As I said before, everything we described is a single head of attention,"}, {"duration": 3.525, "start": 1235.188, "text": "and a full attention block inside a transformer consists of what's"}, {"duration": 4.419, "start": 1238.713, "text": "called multi-headed attention, where you run a lot of these operations in parallel,"}, {"duration": 2.788, "start": 1243.132, "text": "each with its own distinct key query and value maps."}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 1247.42, "text": "GPT-3 for example uses 96 attention heads inside each block."}, {"duration": 2.451, "start": 1252.02, "text": "Considering that each one is already a bit confusing,"}, {"duration": 1.989, "start": 1254.471, "text": "it's certainly a lot to hold in your head."}, {"duration": 4.359, "start": 1256.76, "text": "Just to spell it all out very explicitly, this means you have 96 distinct"}, {"duration": 3.881, "start": 1261.119, "text": "key and query matrices producing 96 distinct attention patterns."}, {"duration": 3.474, "start": 1265.44, "text": "Then each head has its own distinct value matrices"}, {"duration": 3.266, "start": 1268.914, "text": "used to produce 96 sequences of value vectors."}, {"duration": 4.22, "start": 1272.46, "text": "These are all added together using the corresponding attention patterns as weights."}, {"duration": 3.918, "start": 1277.48, "text": "What this means is that for each position in the context, each token,"}, {"duration": 4.77, "start": 1281.398, "text": "every one of these heads produces a proposed change to be added to the embedding in"}, {"duration": 0.852, "start": 1286.168, "text": "that position."}, {"duration": 4.35, "start": 1287.66, "text": "So what you do is you sum together all of those proposed changes, one for each head,"}, {"duration": 3.47, "start": 1292.01, "text": "and you add the result to the original embedding of that position."}, {"duration": 5.061, "start": 1296.66, "text": "This entire sum here would be one slice of what's outputted from this multi-headed"}, {"duration": 5.307, "start": 1301.721, "text": "attention block, a single one of those refined embeddings that pops out the other end"}, {"duration": 0.432, "start": 1307.028, "text": "of it."}, {"duration": 1.868, "start": 1308.32, "text": "Again, this is a lot to think about, so don't"}, {"duration": 1.952, "start": 1310.188, "text": "worry at all if it takes some time to sink in."}, {"duration": 3.938, "start": 1312.38, "text": "The overall idea is that by running many distinct heads in parallel,"}, {"duration": 4.517, "start": 1316.318, "text": "you're giving the model the capacity to learn many distinct ways that context"}, {"duration": 0.985, "start": 1320.835, "text": "changes meaning."}, {"duration": 3.567, "start": 1323.7, "text": "Pulling up our running tally for parameter count with 96 heads,"}, {"duration": 3.227, "start": 1327.267, "text": "each including its own variation of these four matrices,"}, {"duration": 4.586, "start": 1330.494, "text": "each block of multi-headed attention ends up with around 600 million parameters."}, {"duration": 2.606, "start": 1336.42, "text": "There's one added slightly annoying thing that I should really"}, {"duration": 2.774, "start": 1339.026, "text": "mention for any of you who go on to read more about transformers."}, {"duration": 3.512, "start": 1342.08, "text": "You remember how I said that the value map is factored out into these two"}, {"duration": 3.848, "start": 1345.592, "text": "distinct matrices, which I labeled as the value down and the value up matrices."}, {"duration": 4.268, "start": 1349.96, "text": "The way that I framed things would suggest that you see this pair of matrices"}, {"duration": 4.212, "start": 1354.228, "text": "inside each attention head, and you could absolutely implement it this way."}, {"duration": 1.28, "start": 1358.64, "text": "That would be a valid design."}, {"duration": 2.31, "start": 1360.26, "text": "But the way that you see this written in papers and the way"}, {"duration": 2.35, "start": 1362.57, "text": "that it's implemented in practice looks a little different."}, {"duration": 5.489, "start": 1365.34, "text": "All of these value up matrices for each head appear stapled together in one giant matrix"}, {"duration": 5.551, "start": 1370.829, "text": "that we call the output matrix, associated with the entire multi-headed attention block."}, {"duration": 3.766, "start": 1376.82, "text": "And when you see people refer to the value matrix for a given attention head,"}, {"duration": 2.592, "start": 1380.586, "text": "they're typically only referring to this first step,"}, {"duration": 3.962, "start": 1383.178, "text": "the one that I was labeling as the value down projection into the smaller space."}, {"duration": 2.7, "start": 1388.34, "text": "For the curious among you, I've left an on-screen note about it."}, {"duration": 2.334, "start": 1391.26, "text": "It's one of those details that runs the risk of distracting"}, {"duration": 2.453, "start": 1393.594, "text": "from the main conceptual points, but I do want to call it out"}, {"duration": 2.493, "start": 1396.047, "text": "just so that you know if you read about this in other sources."}, {"duration": 4.425, "start": 1399.24, "text": "Setting aside all the technical nuances, in the preview from the last chapter we saw how"}, {"duration": 4.375, "start": 1403.665, "text": "data flowing through a transformer doesn't just flow through a single attention block."}, {"duration": 4.06, "start": 1408.64, "text": "For one thing, it also goes through these other operations called multi-layer perceptrons."}, {"duration": 1.76, "start": 1413.12, "text": "We'll talk more about those in the next chapter."}, {"duration": 4.14, "start": 1415.18, "text": "And then it repeatedly goes through many many copies of both of these operations."}, {"duration": 3.925, "start": 1419.98, "text": "What this means is that after a given word imbibes some of its context,"}, {"duration": 3.316, "start": 1423.905, "text": "there are many more chances for this more nuanced embedding"}, {"duration": 2.819, "start": 1427.221, "text": "to be influenced by its more nuanced surroundings."}, {"duration": 4.007, "start": 1430.94, "text": "The further down the network you go, with each embedding taking in more and more"}, {"duration": 4.108, "start": 1434.947, "text": "meaning from all the other embeddings, which themselves are getting more and more"}, {"duration": 3.957, "start": 1439.055, "text": "nuanced, the hope is that there's the capacity to encode higher level and more"}, {"duration": 4.308, "start": 1443.012, "text": "abstract ideas about a given input beyond just descriptors and grammatical structure."}, {"duration": 3.832, "start": 1447.88, "text": "Things like sentiment and tone and whether it's a poem and what underlying"}, {"duration": 3.418, "start": 1451.712, "text": "scientific truths are relevant to the piece and things like that."}, {"duration": 5.288, "start": 1456.7, "text": "Turning back one more time to our scorekeeping, GPT-3 includes 96 distinct layers,"}, {"duration": 5.353, "start": 1461.988, "text": "so the total number of key query and value parameters is multiplied by another 96,"}, {"duration": 4.644, "start": 1467.341, "text": "which brings the total sum to just under 58 billion distinct parameters"}, {"duration": 2.515, "start": 1471.985, "text": "devoted to all of the attention heads."}, {"duration": 2.98, "start": 1474.98, "text": "That is a lot to be sure, but it's only about a third"}, {"duration": 2.98, "start": 1477.96, "text": "of the 175 billion that are in the network in total."}, {"duration": 2.577, "start": 1481.52, "text": "So even though attention gets all of the attention,"}, {"duration": 4.043, "start": 1484.097, "text": "the majority of parameters come from the blocks sitting in between these steps."}, {"duration": 2.415, "start": 1488.56, "text": "In the next chapter, you and I will talk more about those"}, {"duration": 2.585, "start": 1490.975, "text": "other blocks and also a lot more about the training process."}, {"duration": 4.644, "start": 1494.12, "text": "A big part of the story for the success of the attention mechanism is not so much any"}, {"duration": 4.207, "start": 1498.764, "text": "specific kind of behaviour that it enables, but the fact that it's extremely"}, {"duration": 4.753, "start": 1502.971, "text": "parallelizable, meaning that you can run a huge number of computations in a short time"}, {"duration": 0.656, "start": 1507.724, "text": "using GPUs."}, {"duration": 3.851, "start": 1509.46, "text": "Given that one of the big lessons about deep learning in the last decade or two has"}, {"duration": 4.083, "start": 1513.311, "text": "been that scale alone seems to give huge qualitative improvements in model performance,"}, {"duration": 3.666, "start": 1517.394, "text": "there's a huge advantage to parallelizable architectures that let you do this."}, {"duration": 3.3, "start": 1522.04, "text": "If you want to learn more about this stuff, I've left lots of links in the description."}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 1525.92, "text": "In particular, anything produced by Andrej Karpathy or Chris Ola tend to be pure gold."}, {"duration": 3.16, "start": 1530.56, "text": "In this video, I wanted to just jump into attention in its current form,"}, {"duration": 2.984, "start": 1533.72, "text": "but if you're curious about more of the history for how we got here"}, {"duration": 2.238, "start": 1536.704, "text": "and how you might reinvent this idea for yourself,"}, {"duration": 3.598, "start": 1538.942, "text": "my friend Vivek just put up a couple videos giving a lot more of that motivation."}, {"duration": 2.67, "start": 1543.12, "text": "Also, Britt Cruz from the channel The Art of the Problem has a"}, {"duration": 2.67, "start": 1545.79, "text": "really nice video about the history of large language models."}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 1564.96, "text": "Thank you."}], "video_id": "eMlx5fFNoYc"}